3.2 T2 relaxation, T2* relaxation, and spin echoes

The relaxation time T2 is the time required for the transverse component of M to
decay to 37% of its initial value through irreversible processes. It is also known as
the spin‚Äìspin relaxation time or transverse relaxation time. Recall from Chapter 1 that
M0 is oriented only along the z (B0) axis at equilibrium and that no portion of M0 is in the xy plane. The coherence is entirely longitudinal or parallel to B0. Absorption of energy from a 90‚àò RF pulse as in Figure 2.2 causes M0 to rotate entirely into the xy plane, so that the coherence is in the transverse plane at the end of the pulse. As time elapses, this coherence disappears
while at the same time the protons release their energy and reorient themselves along B0. This disappearing coherence produces the FID described in Chapter 2. As this coherence disappears, the value of M in the xy plane decreases toward 0. T2 or T2‚àó relaxation is the process by which
this transverse magnetization is lost.
A comparison of the microscopic and macroscopic pictures provides additional insight. At the end of the 90‚àò RF pulse, when the protons have absorbed energy and M is oriented in the
transverse plane, each proton precesses at the same frequency ùúî0 and is synchronized at the same point or phase of its precessional cycle. Since a nearby proton of the same type will have
the same molecular environment and the same ùúî0, it can readily absorb the energy that is being released by its neighbor. Spin‚Äìspin relaxation refers to this energy transfer from an excited
proton to another nearby proton (Figure 3.4). The absorbed energy remains as spin excitation

