One important difference between T1 and T2 relaxation is in the inÔ¨Çuence of B0. As mentioned earlier, T1 is very sensitive to B0, with longer T1 times measured for a tissue at higher B0. T2 is relatively insensitive to B0 at the relatively large Ô¨Åeld strengths currently used in MRI. Only at very low B0 (less than 0.05 T) will there be signiÔ¨Åcant changes in T2. The other components of T2‚àó, T2M and T2MS become more prominent at higher B0. Good magnetic Ô¨Åeld uniformity is more difÔ¨Åcult to generate at high magnetic Ô¨Åelds, so that
T2M will be shorter. Greater B0 will also cause greater differences in M0 between two tissues with different magnetic susceptibilities, producing shorter T2MS. The result is that T2-weighted techniques will see little sensitivity to B0 while T2‚àó-weighted techniques will show greater signal differences at higher B0.

